dehesa de abajo, puebla del río, sevilla, andalucía
recordings.rmk: En este lugar se realizan actividades de caza y ganadería a la par que es utilizado como lugar de esparcimiento por los autóptonos. Además es un espacio valioso para la fauna y allí se encuentra la mayor colonia de cigueña blanca sobre acebuche. El hábitat consta de un gran pinar, un bosque adehesado de acebuches, un erial y un sistema dulceacuícola compuesto por el arroyo Majaberraque y la laguna donde desemboca.

El lugar consiste en una serie de plantaciones de arroz, canales de irrigación para éstas cubiertos de vegetación, praderas de almajo y eriales. En aquel momento los canales de riego aún no tenían agua porque no se había plantado aún el arroz, y a causa de la escasez de lluvias primaverales a penas había unos charcones de agua.

Recording taken directly from phone. No editing. 
The bird sang primarily from low brambles on the edge of a narrow reeded ditch. The singing lasted, off and on, for approx. 90 minutes and it was seen to "sing" once in flight, whilst chasing off  European Reed Warbler. 
Occasionally the bird showed very well in the middle of the ditch, feeding on insects on the water surface and it would often favour the new reed growth on the edge of the dyke.

recordings.rmk: Great Reed Warbler making the scratchy call throughout while a Cape Turtle Dove also call throughout the sound clip.

Large Acrocephalus (size of Phyllastrephus!) singing in a bush on the caldera rim. Stayed out of sight, but was not scared off. Bird had a prominent eyeline, very white throat, and rufous back with browner wings. Voice memo from time of: 'rufous back, browner wings, browner tail... Thin eyestripe, pale above [the eye], white throat.. Pale breast and everything... Check out Acrocephalus as well, as this could be some weird vagrant that I just don't recognize.' Some playback was attempted, but due to wind/playback error, I do not believe the bird could hear it. It's behavior and song style did not change before and after the attempt. Unfortunately, camera shutter is associated with Sarah, who was photographing butterflies nearby.
